Congress Goes Home, Washington Quiets Down.
WASHINGTON: Well, Congress will
have gone home by the time this is printed.
A footstep tomorrow will echo through the
marble corridors of the Capitol, a lonesome
thing, disturbing only the stone statues and
the summer visitors. The 80th Congress of the
United States, first session, will have ground to
an end.
The chambers will have a ghostlike silence
Gone will be the hot debate, the flaring tem
pers, the scramble, and the chance passage of
some and the chance loss of other important
legislation. All things which mark the closing
days of any session.
Congressmen this week were thumbing
through piles of correspondence and documenU
accumulated on and In their desks. Most of It
went into the waatebasket That, too, was a
part of session'i end. Secretaries stood in line
in the Capitol's ticket office to buy their
bosses' tickets home. It was all something li'-e
the last days of college.
Cincinnati's Congressmen and Senators will
be on their way home by Monday. All will go
to Columbus on Thursday for the big Ohio Re
publican conclave. Rep. Charles H. Elston and
Rep. William E. Hess later will make their
annual visit to The Snows as guests of Ed D.
Schorr. Sen Robert A. Xaft will go on to the
family's summer home at Murray Bay to rest
from the session and for his six-state western
peech-making tour, announced this week for
September.
JUST A HUNCH as to what will happen at
Columbus:
(1) Sen. John W. Bricker will make hia
long-forecast Indorsement of Taft for Presi
dent In 1948. i ,
(2) Ohio Republicans will declare with one
voice that Taft is their man for '48.
(S) Taft will reply, In effect: "Thank you
very much, fellows. This Is a great honor and
I appreciate it very much. I'U let you know
something in the fall.'
REPRESENTATIVE ELSTON made a
statement this week which was, to me, an
amazing disclosure, and one that I have not
Been printed elsewhere. It was: That the en
tire cost to the taxpayer of officers' and
enlisted men's terminal leave arose out of an
"act of discretion" on the part of the Secretary
f War.
Perhaps it would be better to call it an act
f indiscretion.
The cost of terminal leave will be approxi
"The War Department was not required to
pay officer for accrued leave," Elston said.
"The decision to pay it was an act of discretion
en the part of the Secretary of War. Once it
was paid to officers, however, it was only fair
that it should be paid to enlisted men.
But, if It had never been paid to officers,
no one would ever have thought of claiming it
for enlisted men and the government would
have been saved these billions of dollars."
Elston cited testimony of Brig. Gen. Ira
Swift, General Staff Corps, before the House
Military Affairs Committee December 3, 1915.
"There is an old law which goes back to
1884," General Swift testified, "which authorizes
an officer In the Army a leave of absence on
the basis of 30 days per year, in the discretion
of the Secretary of War. If he gets leave, ho
gets paid while he Is on leave. If he does not
get it, it can accrue for a maximum of four
years.
"Leave of officers has never been a statu
tory right for anybody in the Army. A soldier
er officer gets leave if his services can be
pared, not otherwise. The commanding officer
over that man was always the judge as to
whether they could be spared. Of course, they
could not be spared during the war; however,
the war is over and their services can be spared
now, and there Is no good reason in my mind
why they should not be given leave or pay in
lieu thereof."
Just an $8,500,000,000 reason.
A GOOD FRIEND of Senator Taft's once
said: "He thinks he's a politician and he isn't.
He doesn't know it. but he's a statesman."
The Senator did a couple of things toward
justifying the statement this week. The fiist
came on Tuesday, when he led the fight on the
Republican side of the aisle for approval of the
President's reorganization plan No. 3. This
will permit unification of the several agencies
dealing with housing and home finance under
a single head. Eleven Republicans joined with
36 Democrats to permit the plan to go into
effect.
Now, it must have been a temptation to any
Republican to vote against the plan. It is only
normal in politics to reason; If the other side
wants something, don't give it.
But the Senator believed that this proposal
would reduce the confusion In the housing pic
ture. He voted for It. His Influence very prob
ably led to approval.
The second Instance was the Senator's state
ment in a radio forum broadcast Tuesday
night: "I think the Marshall proposal is bu.v
Ically sound."
Those were strong words for the Ohio Re
publican. They were, perhaps, the strongest
words that have been said In behalf of the plan
since Secretary Marshall announced It in June.
If Taft is for it, It has a far better chance of
getting through the Congress than many of
its friends had thought.
I am surprised that the broadcast got no
wider publicity.
Taft qualified his approval by pointing out
that the Marshall proposal apparently does not
call for additional spending, but for continu
ation of present spending, and calls for furnish
ing goods that will help them help themselves.
Both Taft and Sen. Owen Brewster, Repub
lican, Maine, also on the forum, rapped the
British for using part of the American loan to
buy American tobacco and movies. They said,
also, that the British should have been buying
machines and equipment Instead of food. Pre
sumably, the British, already hungry, should
have gone that much hungrier.
Just to keep the record straight, I inquired
at the British Information Service and got this
breakdown of the amount spent for American
products from the British dollar pool funds
from all sources, Including the loan and exp' Is
from Britain to America between July, 194C
and March, i17: Total spent (in millions of
pounds), 187.2; for food, 68.1; fats and oils, 65;
tobacco, 39.3; cotton, 10.8; timber, 1.8; Iron and
steel, 3.7; wood manufactures, t.4; chemicals
and drugs, 3.5, and miscellaneous manufactures
and raw materials, 24.7. And, in addition, they
paid 14,000,000 pounds as royalties on Amer
ican movies.

General Marshall Reports Fifth Col
WASHINGTON: George C. Marshall,
Secretary of State, gloomily disclosed to
the House Foreign Affairs Committee the
other day that a Soviet fifth column, com
posed mostly of Germans, is working
"night and day" to cause chaos in Germany.
At an off-the-record meeting, frequently in
terrupted by roll calls that kept the members
treking back and fourth between the floor and
the committee room, Marshall, in effect, de
clared: "The Russian game is to keep Germany in
chaos, realizing that desperate, broken, hungry
people are easy prey for Communism and will
turn to Russia for aid."
He emphasized ihat European recovery is
Impossible without ttepped-up German produc
tion, and assured the Congressmen that this
was the unanimous opinion of the "best minds
available." Germany was the huh of European
economy before the war, Marshall pointed out,
and could not be blanked out suddenly without
upsetting the whole European structure.
If Germany becomes a cancer," he warned,
"the thing will spread,"
THE SECRETARY OF STATE implied that
Germany can be made self-sufficient without
again threatening world peace, but indicated
that the problem was to convince France of
this. He declared frankly that economic re
covery in Europe hinged upon the French atti
tude toward Germany, inasmuch as France
fears any program that might develop Ger
many's war potential. This worry is aggra
vated by Communist propaganda, he said.
However, General Marshall insisted that It
Is up to the European nations, "which have to
live with Germany," to decide whether they
can get along economically without her or
whether they would rather risk restoring
healthy German production under Allied occu
pation and control. He stressed that Europe
must work out Its own economic salvation and
adopt a program that will not collapse after
American aid is discontinued.
"There is no magic formula," the Secretary
of State added gravely.
BANISHING A BRASS HAT: Pint-sized,
gallon-voiced Senator Gurney of South Dakota
came out second best in an argument with
Senator Bridges of New Hampshire both Re
publicansinside a Senate Appropriations Sub
committee. The subcommittee was putting the finishing
touches on the $5,616,618,000 military spending
bill, when Bridges, Chairman of the full com
mittee, opened the door. There, big as life, at
the Appropriations Committee table, sat MaJ.
Gen. George J. Richards, the War Depart
ment's budget officer.
Bridges took one look at Richards and de
manded of Gurney:
"What's this man doing here? This is a
rlosed-door meeting and no one is supposed to
be here except committee members and the
clerk."
"Oh it's all right," replied the South
Pakotan. "I took it up with the subcommittee
umn In Germany.
members before you got here. We have decided
to let the General sit in to help us."
"What!" roared Eridges. "Do you mean to
say that General Richards is helping to draft
legislation before this committee? This Is one
of the most absurd things I've ever heard of."
"But but we've agreed " sputtered Gurney.
"I don't care what you've agreed to," thun
dered Bridges. "I'm Chairman of this com
mittee and I say he must leave. I'm not object
ing to General Richards personally, but I won't
have a representative of the War Department,
or any other department, in here helping to
draft legislation affecting his department.
"I think you realize that it would be a ter
rible reflection on the committee if this got
out," Bridges added, glaring at Gurney.
"You're absolutely right," agreed Sen.
Homer Ferguson of Michigan, another Repub
lican. By this time Richards had his papers in
hand and was edging for the door.
"Perhaps I'd better withdraw, gentlemen,"
he said meekly, and was gone quicker than a
buck private jumping to attention.
